deck_excerpt: Start w/ Fiendsmith to set up Wave High King Caesar. Next, Centur-ion Stand and Trudea to get out Primera. Follow up with White Forest combo
deck_description:
Still testing. Super combo. Usually like to start with Fiendsmith Engraver in hand to activate all the way to D/D/D Wave High King Ceaser before Nibiru can be used on you. Then if Centur-ion Stand is in hand, place-discard for cost, set Trudea. Special Trudea, then use its effect to relocate to spell/trap zone & Primera from the deck. Special Primera, on resolution, activate primera to search Wake-up Centur-ion! Place level 8 token, & Synchro using Stand Up (I think, or whatever) into Centur-Ion Legatia. Still haven't normal summoned at this point. If you use Emblema Oath, make sure it's something you're going to use as material (I.e. Primera) or you will be Centur-ion Extra Deck Locked. So from here you can normal summon a White forest monster and that combo begins.You will want to get to Diabel & Silhouhatte Rabbit on the field for a 3-negate trap card that will activate during your opponents turn. In your opponent's turn & if you do not have Crimson Dragon on the field, but you have Diabel, you could use Silvy or Rucia of the White Forest to special summon itself (Shuffeling Rciela back into the Extra deck as cost) during your opponent's turn on to your field, for a disruption. Any special summon will trigger the field spell Stand Up & you could synchro off Diabell & the lvl 4 tuner for a Centur -ion Synchro level 12. But you may want to use Diabel's effect during your opponents turn to special summon Zapper Shrimp from the Extra deck before using the disruptions mentioned above, first. From here you can synchro for Chaos Angel or if you have another lvl 2, synchro for Crimson Dragon. If Crimson Dragon & a lvl 12 synchro monster is on the field while on your oppenents turn, or during turn 2, use it's quick effect to target the lvl12 synchro beast, & synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. Activate it's effect & it's game!

Please comment for suggestions & combos!

*If used lvl 6 tuner synchro monster for Diabel's synchro summon, you can add to your hand 1 spell/trap from the Graveyard. For this situation, I probably had already sent a spell/trap hand trap card, like "Crossout Designator." Add that card back to hand, set before ending the turn. That way I can negate imperm when I plan to activate a monster effect on my opponents turn. I do not want crimson dragon or Hot red Dragon impermed. 

*To get Crimson Dragon out on your opponents turn with Diabel & disruptions during your opponents turn: Diabel quick effect to send spell/trap to special summon Zapper Shrimp. After resolution, since a spell/trap was sent to activate a monster effect, special summon Astellar of the White Forest from the Graveyard. Don't chain Zapper yet since Astellar is not on the board yet. Once on board, use Zapper's quick effect to synchro off for Crimson Dragon using Diabel (lvl 8), Astellar of the White Forest (lvl 2), & Zapper Shrimp (lvl 2 - Tuner). Use Crimson Dragon's quick effect to get out hot red boss during your opponents turn for game!
A deck based on cards Jonouchi used throughout the duelist kingdom manga arc with some additional cards and doubles to reach 40 cards

3. Discard a Winged Beast, search Dark Simorgh and Bird of Bringing

4. Normal Summon Bringing (extra normal with Beginning), Bringing search Elborz or Sky Battle if you have Rainbow

5. Link Summon Hraevelsgr 

The turn is usually dependent on the hand, so therefore I cannot outline exact combos. If you have any suggestions, please let me know!

deck_name: A Mecha Fan's Guide to Centur-Ion (July 2024)
deck_excerpt: ATTENTION MECHA FANS, the Centur-Ion ladies have arrived in Masterduel!
deck_description:
ATTENTION MECHA FANS, a new mecha archetype has arrived in Masterduel, and they are none other than Centur-Ions! These ladies combine together with their pilot, machine and spirit partner to synchro summon level 12 boss monsters during your turn and your opponent's turn!
 
Level 12 Synchros are summoned like constantly, leading to the summon of either Legatia (draw 1, destroy 1) or Auxilia (search 1). Both of these mechanical femme fatales generate advantage during the End Phase, placing your spent Centur-Ion starters from the GY and Banished pile in the backrow where they can be used again for next turn. 
 
The hyper consistent nature of Centur-Ions means that this deck can play a whopping 21 staples, meaning you'll always win the "Maxx C" minigame, handtrap your opponent to a standstill, and outgrind your opponent with sheer mechanical might and the power of friendship!
 
YOUR DRILL WILL REACH MASTERS WITH CENTUR-ION! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The CENTURION deck core is compact because of it's amazing consistency and 1-card starters being only a mere 16 cards. The only Centur-Ion cards that aren't a 1 card starter are Emet VI, Gargoyle II and Phalanx. x2 Bonfire is also another starter since it searches out Trudea. This brings the deck's total to 14 one-card starters, meaning that having them in your opening hand is extremely likely. If you have multiple starters in your hand, you can use them as extenders whenever your opponent interrupts you, so this deck is naturally very resilient to handtraps. 
 
 
STAPLES compose the rest of this deck. 21 staple cards are used because of Centur-Ion's hyper consistency! The usual "Maxx C" package is used, so that the pilot has as much chance to win the Maxx C minigame. Psyframes are used as well, since the deck does many of it's plays without monsters on the field, giving the player ample chances to punish their opponent with Gamma, which in turn can be used to make Omega or Baronne. The 1-of staples are Crossout targets, but in general Nibiru, Imperm, Trust, Talents, Magnumhut, Druiswyrm, etc. are very useful cards as well!
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Centur-Ion's current main combo is linear, and all cards do the same thing and lead to the same outcome. This means that this deck is extremely predictable, very simple and easy to learn. As said before, most Centur-Ion cards are one card starters, and if your first starter gets interrupted/negated, the other starters in your hand can also act as extenders to continue on your combo. For example, if Primera got impermed/veiler'd, you can summon Primera and continue comboing to get your level 12 synchro boss monster, Legatia. 
 
Since the gameplan hinges the success of the Centur-Ion combo, the pilot must do whatever they can to simplify the opponent's gamestate and bait interruption. Baronne (Horus + Vision Resonator) can be summoned before attempting anything else to insulate your combo lines. Photon Lord can also be made with 2 level 8s (usually 2 Horus monsters) to negate monster effects.
 
Here are Centur-Ion 1-card combo:
 
Primera = Legatia (Pop monster, draw 1 and resource generator) + Calamity Lock (Or Omni-negate with Blazar Dragon) + follow-up 
  1. Normal summon Primera to search Stand-Up! 
  2. Activate Stand-Up! Use Stand-Up's effect to send 1 card from hand to GY to place Trudea on the backrow as a continuous trap. 
  3. Special summon Trudea from the backrow. 
  4. Activate Trudea's effect to place itself on the backrow and Emeth VI from deck on the backrow. 
  5. Special summon Emeth VI from the backrow. 
  6. Synchro summon Legatia using Primera + Emeth VI.
  7. Activate Legatia's on-summon effect to pop a monster with highest ATK your opponent controls (if applicable) and draw 1 card. 
  8. During the End Phase, activate Legatia's effect to place Primera on the backrow as a continuous trap.
  9. During the opponent's Main Phase, special summon Primera (CL1) and Trudea as a level 8 (CL2) from the backrow. 
  10. CL1 Primera to search a Centur-Ion card (usually Bonds since it's excellent follow-up), and CL2 Stand-Up! to synchro summon for Crimson Dragon, CL3 activate Emeth VI in the GY placing Trudea in the backrow. Resolve Stand-Up! Synchro summoning Crimson Dragon using Primera + Emeth VI. 
  11. Activate Crimson Dragon CL1 to search Synchro Rumble from deck, Activate Crimson Dragon CL2 targeting Legatia to synchro summon either Blazar (onmi-negate) or Supernova (banish entire enemy field) from Extra Deck.
With one singular card, you've locked your opponent out of the game, and you have ample follow-up for next turn's OTK! (So unfair, I can feel a King Calamities ban on the horizon).
 
The win condition of Centur-Ion is to outgrind your opponent with immense resource generation with Legatia's +1 draw, Auxila's search, and end phase recursion of Centur-Ion monster cards. If you've slowed down your opponent enough with your handtraps, Supernova and Blazar, you should be able to out-resource your opponent and win!
 
Alternatively if you activated Dimension Shifter, you can still do the above combo, but summon Auxilia instead so you can place Primera in your backrow from Banishment. The best card to search with Auxilia is Stand Up! So you can synchro summon on your opponent's turn, or if you already have it, search for Phalanx instead. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If your opponent is targeting your Centur-Ion monster, you can "dodge" their targeting effect if Emeth VI is in your hand or GY! Simply chain Emeth VI's effect to place your monster in the backrow! 
  • Dimension Shifter shuts off many common handtraps that slow down Centur-Ion like Maxx "C", Droll, Ghost Ogre, Ghost Belle and Effect Veiler! If you have the chance, always shotgun your Shifter! 
  • Bystials can trigger Stand Up! By summoning on your opponent's turn, and if Primera/Trudea are on the field, you can synchro summon either Baronne or Chaos Angel! 
  • If your opponent targets your continuous trap card Centur-Ion monster on the backrow during the main phase, you can "dodge" their targeting effect by simply chaining their quick effect summon! 
  • Centur-Ion Phalanx can banish your continuous trap card monsters in the backrow to summon them next stand-by phase. That's because monsters treated as continuous traps in the backrow are still counted as "monsters" and Phalanx reads "target 1 face-up monster card on the field."
  • When choosing either Blazar or Supernova to synchro summon with Crimson Dragon, ask yourself - what counters my opponent more, a omni-negate (Blazar) or field banish (Supernova)? 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Centur-Ion's entrance into Masterduel certainly has made waves in higher levels of play! Even though the infamous "Calamity Lock" has been banned recently, Centur-Ion can still consistently win vs. top meta decks because of their extreme consistency, 21 staple cards, and robust gameplan! This mid-range deck many not have as much power as Yubel and Snake-Eyes, but it sure makes up for it with it's reliability on Masterduel ladder! Plus, I personally think mechas and mecha pilots are the coolest thing ever, especially in Yugioh, so this is my new favourite deck for the time being. When the next Centur-Ion support comes out, the deck will surely it'll be good enough to pierce the heavens!
 
GLHF Duelists!

good deck. try it or be sad

This deck doesn't include the Diabellstar package in order to keep its price below $140 side deck included, i'll explain my deckbuilding decisions as follows:

Given that the absence of the Diabellstar Engine represents a heavy hit on consistency, i've decided to use 3 Poplar (1 more than the usual) that can be used both as starters and extenders and 2 Pot of Prosperity (I think 3 would be excessive, besides you could end up drawing 2 of them turn 1).

Following this line, Snake-Eye Birch works pretty fine as a free extender in case of being ashed (the best case scenario because you could link into Hiita and then Promethean from 2 bodies), or being impermed/veiled. I think 2 Snake-Eye Birch are enough.

Zombie Vampire is there just in case you brick into Fire King, you could turn Kirin+Garunix into a Zombie Vampire hoping to mill a Snake-Eye to summon with the same effect, specially useful during mirrors. If you brick into Fire King against a skilled player, you're dead anyways, so by using Zombie Vampire you have the chance of end up on a decent board.

3 Book of Eclipse as a cheap way of boardbreaking, you could use Forbbiden Droplet instead. Both are great options in my opinion.

1 Nibiru as a Crossout Designator target, the 3 Crossouts are necessary for keeping the consistency of the deck without the recursion offered by the Diabellstar package, 2 Original Sinful Spoils instead of 1 are also a necessary evil to not brick or to be able to extend or bridge into Snake Eyes.

Bystial Magnamhut because we're entering into a more diverse format with a lot of Dark/Light monsters, also works as an extender if you're veiled, can be changed for Droll & Lock Bird as a Crossout Designator target.

Circle of Fire King and Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf as great recursion tools. Kikinagashi Fucho to stall a turn against Tenpai in case you have to go first, if you have Snake-Eye Birch on hand you can XYZ summon it easy.

Your desirable end board is: Apollousa 1600ATK (2 monster negations) + Number 38: Hope Harbinger (Spell Negation) + Amblowhale (Recursion tool and Promethean target) with Garunix and Promethean Princess on Graveyard. Number 38 also protects Apollousa from being hit by battle.

Regarding to Side Deck: Every Spell is a boardbreaker tool in case you go second, every Trap is a Win Condition in case you go first. Solemn Judgement is there to protect your field, be careful with the Fire King Island mandatory effect.

Synchron deck that aims to synchro vomit and end on a couple big stupid dragons.

Raidraptor deck, aiming to vomit xyz and combo into the big birds, occasionally on the opponent's turn.

If evil enough, it can summon Kali Yuga on the opponent's turn.

deck_excerpt: The Hero Emerges through the darkness to protect the weak.
deck_description:
This is a really fun deck to play with, especially with friends and even on a competitive level. You'll always want to go second with this deck due to the lack of negates this deck has to offer, which is why I added in a few other cards. This deck was inspired by Team Sammurai X1, though I took bits and pieces of what I liked and add other neat things. You won't find many hero decks that are super versatile, so I hope this build stands out.

 

When playing with this deck, I can't help but feel a Jaden Yuki vibe by being able to have Burstinatrix and Avian in your deck, along with the Flame Wingman. Of course, you can always remove that package with something else. However, I found this deck was incredibly consistent. Ash Blossom can be a pain for this deck, which is why I added the three E - Emergency Calls. Not only are they not once per turn, but they'll be a perfect bait, not to mention, resource to build your hand the way you see fit.

 

The main cards for my bread and butter combo are

Vision Hero Farris X3

Vision Hero Increase X2

Vision Hero Vyon X2

Destiny Hero - Malicious X3

Elemental Hero Burstinatrix

Elemental Hero Avian

Evil Hero Adusted Gold

Miracle Fusion

Polymerization

Dark Calling

Xtra Hero Infernal Devicer

Xtra Hero Wonder Driver

Xtra Hero Cross Crusader

Elemental Hero Cosmo Neos

Elemental Hero Sunrise

Elemental Hero Grandmerger

Elemental Hero Flame Wingman

Evil Hero Malicious Bane

 

The Combo will be as followed

- Activate Farris' effect and discard 1 hero from your hand to special summon it to the field

 - Activate Farris' effect and Add Vision Hero Increase to the S/T Zone

- Activate Increases effect and tribute Farris to special summon self to field

- Activate Increases effect and special summon Vylon to the field 

- Acivate Vylon's effect and send Malicious to GY

- Activate Malicious' effect and banish self to special summon Malicious from deck

- Link Malicious and Increase into Devicer

- Activate Devicer's effect and reveal Flame Wingman (Add Burst and Avian to hand)

- Activate Vylon's effect and banish Farris  to add Poly

- Activate Poly to summon Sunrise (Avian and Burstinatrix)

- Activate Sunrise's effect (Add Miracle Fusion)

- Activate Malicious effect and banish self to special summon Malicious from deck

- Link Devicer and and Vylon to summon Wonder Driver

- Activate Miracle fusion to banish Burst and Avian for Grandmerger (Under Wonder)

- Activate Wonder Driver to set Poly

- Link Malicious and Wonder Drive into Cross Crusader

- Activate Cross Crusader's effect and summon Malicious from GY

- Activate Cross Crusader's effect and tribute Malicious to add Adusted Gold

- Discard Adusted Gold to add Dark Calling to hand

- Activate Dark Calling and banish Adusted gold and Farris to summon Bane

 

***If Going second***

- Activate Malicious bane's effect to clear opponent's board

- If a monster can't be destroyed, attack with Grand Merger

- Once a monster is destroyed by Grand Merger, tribute it for Cosmo Neos

- Activate Cosmo Neos' effect to stop foe from using card effects

- OTK and wipe out opponent

 

You have multiple options on getting Farris and one hero to your hand. Now, unfortunately, if you play Fusion Destiny, you are locked out of non-dark attribute monsters. So as an extender, if you find yourself with fusion destiny in your hand after the combo, go ahead and activate it.

 

- Activate Fusion Destiny and send Denier and Plasma to summon Phoenix Enforcer

 

It's just one extra step, Phoenix Enforcer is a pretty sick card, and it really adds on the Aster Phoenix vibe as well. I also went ahead and created a combo that works with just fusion destiny, making it that if for some unknown reason, you can't get your primary combo started, this will be another way to set up your board and obliterate your opponent

 

Combo #2: Dark Lock

- Activate Fusion Destiny (Send Denier and Malicious to grave) summon Phoenix

- Banish Malicious from Grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Activate Denier and special summon to field and return banished Malicious to deck

- Link Denier and Malicious into Infernal Devicer

- Activate Devier's effect and add Burstinatrix and Avian to hand

- Banish Malicious from grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Link Phoenix and Malicious to summon Cross Cruesader

- Activate Cross Cruesader to special summon Phoenix to field

- Banish Malicious from grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Activate Cross Cruesdader and tribute Malicious to add Farris from deck to hand

- Discard Avian and summon Farris

- Activate Farris' effect to add Increase to the S/T zone

- Activate Increase's effect and tribute Farris to special summon Increase

- Activate Increase's effect and special summon Vylon 

- Activate Vylon's effect and send Shadow Mist to grave and add Adusted Gold to hand

- Activate Vylon's effect and banish Shadow Mist and add Poly to hand

- Activate Poly to fuse Vylon and Increase and summon Adoration / Trinity

***If your opponent has a monster that can't be destroyed by effect, summon Trinity

- Activate Adusted Gold and add Dark Calling

- Activate Dark Calling and banish Malicious and Adusted Gold to summon Malicious Bane

 

This combo feels really good and so you have two set ways on playing the deck with this build. Keep in mind, hand traps can be annoying, so be aware of any your opponent might bright. As for your side deck goes, I would add cards that make going first easier, such as your own hand traps, solemn Strike, etc. In other words, you want to be able to stop or at least, limit the boards your opponent makes.

 

I included Mudragon and Starving Venom along with the Super Poly so that way you can break your opponent's board or make some follow up plays. Remember, heroes aren't made for long games, so you'll want to finish off your opponent as quickly as possible. I hope you guys found this deck to be interesting and wish to give it a try. I'll be working on more decks as well that cover certain archetypes such as the Dark Magician, Cyber Dragons, Blue-Eyes, etc.

deck_excerpt: Floowandereeze Going 2nd build. Side deck is to go first. This deck also uses 1 new card from Infinite Forbidden (INFO) set.
deck_description:
Side deck: For the side, I based it on going 1st since the only time your going use it is if you choose to go first game 2 or if you face a tenpai player and they make you go first which is the majority of the time.

Grave of the Ancient Organism ----> Threatening Roar

Lose One Turn -----> Dimensional Barrier 

These side deck changes if your perfer to use Triple Tactics Thrust more when siding or if you feel there is too much back row destruction. Iam just testing the floodgate traps at the moment.

Extra deck: Winter cherries targets(meta dependent) / Ultimate Slayer targets (conflicts with shifter) / Generic XYZ's and Link monsters.

Notes: The new card from the Infinite Forbidden set called Spell card "Soul Exchange" is a very explosive card when breaking boards going 2nd. When mixed with Dimensional Shifter the effect of Soul Exchange, not only are you tributing their monsters but also banishing them from the game. Since the majority of the format is using their extra deck as a second deck, especially in this Fiendsmith meta that we are in currently.

This deck has a lot of diversity and can be played in many ways.

1. #40: try to summon #40 and activate the effect, and use a rank-up spell to pop every other monster on the board, and deal huge damage to the enemy

2. #88 (hard/bad): To pull that off, you want to summon #88 and activate the effect, also banish terror baby in the gy to make 88 invincible to card effects. you might want to switch some cards in the deck like adding swords of revealing lights

3. 1tk: look up a video on youtube on how to do the 1tk, only one card is needed to do so and it works on turn one. add terraforming to make it easier

4. just everything: use everything to make the game as diverse as possible!

Tip: you can revive numbers with perform puppet, if you manage to banish it (its easy with dreary doll!).

 

Good luck and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Zombie swordsmen here to wreck your opponent's day.
deck_description: Ash Blossom serves a dual purpose here as both a hand trap and being able to be used to go into Squiresaga. Squiresaga can banish your zombies to trigger their effects and its own effects. Samuraisaga is mostly just a beatstick - you'll be using it to go into Shogunsaga which will then banish Samuraisaga to go up to 5500 ATK to become a better beatstick. Gold Sarcophagus functions as a searcher that can also trigger Shiranui on-banish effects. Sunsaga can recycle your banished Synchros then pop your opponent's cards. Shiranui Style Samara is very useful for its draw effect, since you can return 2 of your banished zombies (as long as they have 0 defense) to the deck then draw a card - recycling and draw power. It also gets treated as the Shiranui field spell, and some Shiranui cards get better effects when the field spell is up. The actual Field spell isn't being used here, because it's not really that good. Necroface is there for additional banished card recycling.

Majespecters center around tributing their monsters with their Spells and Traps to disrupt your opponent and destroy their board, and they're also very consistent thanks to their massive searching power. After being Tributed, they can come back fairly easily thanks to being Pendulum monsters. Since they're effect monsters, they can be used to go into Exceed The Pendulum to get 3 downward link arrows.

deck_name: WHAT WILL THE CURRENT COMBO KING D/D/D LIKE? THIS IS HOW I USE IT - RANKED SEASON 32
deck_description: The Season 32 of Master Duel Ranked has begun. Today I will start ranked duel with King D/D/D deck. WHAT WILL THE CURRENT COMBO KING D/D/D LIKE? THIS IS HOW I USE IT - RANKED SEASON 32. Below is the deck profile for everyone to refer to.

main goal is to end on:

beatrice

kristya

red-eyes zombie dragon lord

doomking ballerdroch

Zombie World 

+ 2 cards in hand.

Do you like Fusion spam? Me too!

Don't use Dark Law together with the other Masked HEROs, as their effects won't go off due to them requiring cards to be sent to the GY - Dark Law causes your opponent's cards to be banished instead of going to the GY.

Shadow Mist is a critical searcher for the deck. His effect lets you search out a HERO if he's sent to the GY, which is incredibly easy to do thanks to Polymerization, Vision HERO Vyon, and Mask Change. He can also search out a Mask Change if he's special Summoned (such as with Solid Soldier), but you can't use both of those effects on the same turn. If you want to trigger both, you can set Mask Change after you Special Summon him, then use it during your opponent's turn for a Dark Law play to trigger his search effect. I myself usually just use the HERO search effect, though, as I find it more useful.

Blazeman lets you search out Polymerization on summon, but you can also use him to send another Elemental HERO to the GY to become that Attribute. Useful for Mask Change plays. Like Shadow Mist, you can only use one of the effects per turn.

Vision HERO Vyon can send a HERO from the deck to the GY on Summon, so you can use him to proc Shadow Mist's search effect. He can also banish a HERO from the GY to search out Polymerization. The first effect is a hard once per turn, while the second is a soft once per turn. Unlike Shadow Mist and Blazeman, you can use both on the same turn.

For Fusion spam, you're going to want to go into Elemental HERO Sunrise. He can search out Miracle Fusion on summon, which lets you turn him into Wake Up Your Elemental HERO right after that. If you have a Polymerization or another Miracle Fusion, you can summon out another Sunrise or another HERO Fusion.

In most situations, you'll want to use Polymerization before you use Miracle Fusion. Miracle Fusion banishes from the field and GY to Fusion Summon, so you can use the monsters you just sent to the GY with Poly for another Fusion Summon.

Keep in mind that Favorite Contact does not treat the Special Summon as a Fusion Summon.

deck_name: [1st Place] Tam Yee Luk -  Asia Championship 2000
deck_description: That was the 1st place deck by Tam Yee Luk from the Asia Championship 2000. It was held in Tokyo on August 20th, and was the first international tournament. This premiere event was a big deal considering the World Championship was still years away (2003). Tam Yee Luk was from Hong Kong, and won with the Cannon Burn deck; as opposed to a more traditional beatdown strategy. As such, the deck's fan name would be a popular Judo phrase, translated to "Softness overcomes hardness" due to its use of weaker monsters. The deck, as its traditional name alludes to, revolves around Cannon Soldier inflicting burn damage. This is backed up by a consistent rotation of monsters & resources like: Sangan, Magician of Faith, and Ultimate Offering. Comparatively to Good Stuff, this was a bit of a gimmick deck. Also keep in mind that the meta at the time, Deck Destruction was also popular. Since Cyber Jar & Morphing Jar could replenish the hands, this gave an advantage to Tam Yee Luk via more Cannon Soldier fodder. This was a deck built around countermeasures to the meta, even if the deck did have inherent issues such as the large deck size. You could argue that luck, as well as the tournament’s setup had some influence in the outcome, but it certainly took a level of skill to reach the summit.

deck_excerpt: Control deck with a repeatable removal spell in the DMZ
deck_description:
Playing a control deck against 3 other opponent's is pretty hard but if theres anything that could to it it's a combination of eldlich lab and dogmatika. Surely searching and activating sixth sense multiple times will do the trick right? Then try and kill people with Abom and Avram from there

Getting into a bit more detail about the deck our deckmaster Santa Claws acts as a repeatable kaiju, We can use him up to 5 times in a standard game, Santa doesn't really have any synergy with the rest of the deck so if you want depending on your meta you can swap him out with Archfiend Eccentrick who while being worse removal for monsters, is also an MST and is normal summonable if ya wanna make plays with Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous or Muckraker From the Underworld

Next up we'll talk about the individual engines inside the deck

Labrynth

Now everyone knows that lab is crazy, but its especially crazy in domain format cause we get to abuse Sixth Sense which will form our decks main engine. Cards like Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle , Labrynth Set-Up , and Farewelcome Labrynth can search it while Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle and Redeemable Jar can let us use it repeatedly. We also have Lilith, Lady of Lament which has a chance to search it, make sure to reveal Waking the Dragon as one of the cards for intimidation.

Alongside all the pros above, thanks to the multiplayer nature of the format the battle traps that Labrynth Archfiend can search like cylinder or the mirror forces become really good burn/boardwipes against a mutual enemy, the servants can draw cards, spam the board for extra deck plays, and Arias the Labrynth Butler is a turn 0 play. In addition to all of this Lab synergizes very well with our next engine

Dogmatika

We're not doing much with our extra anyway so why not throw in a dogmatika engine, this also gives us access to Dogmatika Punishment an extremely powerful normal spell for our lab engine, our extra includes a bunch of extremely good sends, Herald of the Arc Light can search Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended , N'tss and Malong give us extra removal, Omega lets us recycle and Granguignol the Dusk Dragon can summon out Despian Luluwalilith , And maximus can send any 2 of those!

Eldlich

Now finally is our least important engine, most of the reason we're playing them is specifically Eldlich the Golden Lord whos a giant beater that can come back a repeatedly, Cursed Eldland can draw us cards every turn but keep in mind it stops non zombies from attacking, so if you want to make a push youll need to use eldlich's 2nd eff or something to get rid of it, otherwise all the trap monsters become pretty good cards while eldlich is out and if hes not then they can at least be used to make extra deck plays. Silhouhatte Rabbit can search them out and turn them into mst's if you've got spare material around.
I wanted to try to build a deck with a backup boss monster. I think is fun trying to come back to the times where you have 2+ boss monsters in the deck and combine it. Just a fun deck

deck_excerpt: Winged Beasts, Dragons and Synchro Summons
deck_description:
And old deck I made back when Frog Quasar was a top tier deck (last 5D's era sets). This was for casual games, but it was suprinsigly decent against more competitive decks. This deck is very outdated to the point of being unplayable today. Some notes to keep in mind:

  • Blizzard the Far North can summon another copy of itself, what allowed for this deck to use Red Nova Dragon, which would hit the field with at least 5000 ATK. Pair this with the ability Dragunity cards had of bringing level 8 synchro monsters out and this dumb combo is more or less worth the deck space.
  • Dragunity at the time would use Stardust Assault Mode. Because of the Blackwing engine, there is no space in the main deck for it, but I would side it if I felt like I needed.
  • Dark Simorgh and Stardust combined would be more than enough protection against most forms of removal the opponent had.
  • Super Polymerization was there along with Doppelwarrior and Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste to counter Shooting Quasar Dragon. Draco-Equiste then could use Quasar's effect against the opponent. This strategy worked against Stardust Dragon and Trishula too. A specific albeit dumb for the time strategy that worked more times than it should have. Doppelwarrior was the warrior monster of choice because it would synergize with the deck's main strategy on its own, preventing it from becoming a dead draw.
  • Kalut the Moon Shadow was there to guarantee Shura the Blue Flame could proc its effect, searching for Gale the Whirlwing, what lead to Blackwing Armor Master.
  • Dragunity Aklys serves as extra fodder for Cards of Consconance along with Phalanx, and the paired with Dragunity Legionnaire would become a complementary form of removal.
  • Zephyros the Elite can be realiably used to reset Dragon Ravine, Dragunity Dux, Dragunity Legionnaire, Blizzard the Far North and Gale the Whirlwind. It also allowed Dragunity Legionnaire to be used to summon Dragunity Knight - Vajrayanna.

deck_excerpt: A galaxy-eyes deck that has undergone several revisions and can usually end on 2-3 negates with a very low chance of bricking.
deck_description:
Ok, so everyone knows that GE is nowhere near "meta".  But, I've found some good lines in this deck that will typically let you end on 2-3 negates.

I'll walk you through a line with an "ideal" hand, say, a Galaxy Soldier (GS), Photon Delta Wing (PDW), Photon Orbital (PO), Foolish Burial, and Photon Emperor (PE).  (You always want to go first with this deck btw)  Activate GS and send PE as cost.  CH1 activate GS to add Galaxy Summoner (GSu) to hand, CH2 to bring back PE to field.  You'll have 2 normal summons now.  Activate PO to attach to whatever, then send to grave to add a Tachyon Primal (TP) to hand.  Normal summon PDW, activate to add a 2nd PDW to field.  xyz summon Galaxy Photon Dragon (GPD).  Activate GPD to add galaxy hundred (GH).  Activate GH to send Photon Jumper (PJ).  Activate PJ to add whatever, but Hyper Galaxy (HG) is a good pick because it allows you to disrupt opponent's boards and then look at/destroy their extra deck on the next turn.  Galaxy Expedition (GE) is also a good pick if you want more rank 8s.  Normal summon PSu through PE's effect, use it to bring back PJ.  On PJ's summon, user GPD to make it lvl 8.  Activate PSu to make GS lvl 4.  xyz Starliege Blast.  xyz Photon Lord.  Activate TP to summon to your field and add a Tachyon Transmigration to hand.  Use Foolish to send Galactic Spiral Dragon (GSD), use GSD's effect to bring it back, xyz Dragluxion, use Dragluxion's effect to add a second TT, then use the other effect to xyz Number 38.  Set your two TTs and pass turn.  You now have 2 omnichains, a monster negate, a spell negate, and anti-targeting, anti-destruction protection on your whole field.  Now you just hope they don't superpoly you and ruin your whole board :)

deck_excerpt: An Insect Pile deck that can actually put up a fight
deck_description:
Historically, Insect decks have had a rough time being able to keep up in most formats. The only notable insect archetype having any real impact being Inzektor. And it's easy to see why, after Inzektor was squashed by Konami. Not a Single Insect based archetype has come out of the woodwork of Konami's think tank has had any where near the same impact or playability of THE best insect archetype to date. 

And as such, the relagation of insect decks resorting to "Insect Good Stuff" seemed to be permanent. Until Now. I will certainly not make the claim that this is the pinnacle of Insect Pile decks. Nor will I claim that I am incredible at deck building. I have however, been theory crafting an insect deck since the debut of the Beetrooper archetype (which ironically are not bees, they're beetles). And as such it has gone through many iterations in that time, landing on this deck profile. 

Like most good stuff decks this incorperates many of the only playable insects into a single deck. Using Beetroopers as the core of the strategy, this deck is able to weave through a veritable swath of potential main deck lines capable of landing on wildly different boards. The most optimal of which ends on at least 2 negates or a pop with a scary moth on field. That being said, not many duelists (or decks) are able to out "Normal Summon Scary Moth and Pass". 

The strategy notably has a few major weak points.

The first point being Nibiru, like most combo decks; Nibiru neutrers the strategy as it has no real way to play through a well timed Nibiru.

The second point being Droll and Lock Bird, this deck relies heavily on searching; and as such finds itself dead on arrival to the activation of Droll. 

And the last and most final point, interaction. Konami has printed a lot of interaction points for insects, however, almost all involve monsters. and not but maybe a total of less than 10 insect monsters or insect connected cards that have the ability to do anything at all related to spells or traps. None of which are negates. And of the negates Insects do have, almost all require the monster to be on field. The only acception to that rule being the Beetrooper counter trap. 

These do limit the deck, however the ability to weave through different lines and multiple points of interaction makes the strategy more than playable in the hands of an experienced and flexibly thinking duelist. 

So if you're interested in playing a rouge deck that has a nack for catching your opponent off guard, give it a try.

deck_name: Infernobles on a budget (post isolde ban)
deck_description: Infernoble on a budget, still testing but should be pretty good (might swap the second dempsey and charles into something else later on)

The decision to main Crossout in this list is due to Raider's Knight being the clearest target of Imperm/Veiler/Mourner

Soul Release in the side deck is mainly due to the prevalence of Snake-Eyes interaction for the grave.
Targets you're looking to hit are Garunix, Promethean Princess, Ponix, Original Sin, Wanted, Oak, and Flamberg if against Fire-King.

Overall though, board breakers are currently being used against Fiendsmith, so possibly replace Soul Release for Droplet or Raigeki


The deck is 43 cards.
28 Engine + 1 Foolish Burial + 3 Swallow's Cowrie
11 Non-Engine

If you wish to reduce down to 40 cards,
You can cut Swallow's Cowrie 
OR
You can cut Phantom Knights' RUM Force + Foolish Burial + Simorgh, Bird of Perfection

I couldn't make room for Evilswarm Nightmare in this list, but if you decide to take out Phantom Knights' RUM Force, you should replace
Dark Requiem XYZ dragon + Dark Rebellion Dragon
w/
Evilswarm Nightmare + Raidraptor Revolution Falcon

The second copy of Raider's Knight could be replaced with Evilswarm Nightmare.
(Just remember to try and use Raidraptor - Roost to return your only copy of Raider's Knight for a better grind game)

deck_excerpt: "Lab engine is just a boring slog that takes no skill to play" I disagree! Let me show you why!

deck_description:
The main strategy is have Deuterion, Hydrogedon, Oxygedon and Water Dragon Cluster into hand or graveyard, Bonding - DHO set and activate it on oponent Battle Phase to summon Water Dragon Cluster, activate Water Dragon Cluster ability to sacrifice it and summon both Water Dragon in Defense Position in the End Phase so you can change them both to Attack Position in your Main Phase.

How to play:

Use the Skill to discard Deuterion / Hydrogedon and search for Oxygedon or discard Oxygedon and search for Deuterion / Hydrogedon.

Use the ability of Deuterion to search for Bonding - DHO.

In case you are missing one of the pieces, you can use Foolish Burial to send one of the monster to the Graveyard or using your own Galaxy Cyclone to destroy your set Bonding - DHO and remove it from the Graveyard to search for the Water Dragon Cluster.

deck_name: FTK Degen's Guide to Gimmick Puppet (Post-INFO)
deck_excerpt: With the support from INFO, Quattro's Gimmick Puppets transformed from an obscure, weak anime deck into a nearly unstoppable FTK powerhouse!
deck_description:
With the support from Infinite Forbidden, Quattro's Gimmick Puppets transformed from an obscure, weak anime deck into a nearly unstoppable first turn kill powerhouse! Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls renders your Gimmick Puppet combo UNAFFECTED by monster based handtraps as well as monster interruption! With this absolutely cracked field spell, going first and second suddenly became much easier for the strategy, especially since Gimmick Puppets burn for the entirety of your opponent's lifepoints going first, and going second, opponent's boards are naturally cleared as you fly through the combos.
 
Rouge Doll is another incredible card, acting as this deck's "Exosister Martha," summoning herself and another Gimmick Puppet from deck for further XYZ plays! Not only that, she recurs herself the GY as soon as she hits hit (for ex. Getting detached for foolish'd) granting this strategy a robust grind game. Little Soldiers gives the deck it's best normal summon and 1-card combo in the form of a foolish burial. Cattle Scream gives the deck a free body to XYZ summon with and more ways to summon monsters on your opponent's side of the field to enable the burn FTK. 
 
The support for Gimmick Puppet is SO CRACKED that it constantly makes tops in tournaments! Check out the NAWCQ and EUWCQ decklists and you'll find a few Gimmick Puppet lists in there! This current list is my own version from the topping Gimmick Puppet decks. I thought the burn FTK was just like it's namesake - a gimmick. But in reality, I was pleasantly surprised during testing that Quattro's macabre puppets can really win games with their "fan service!" 
 
Gimmick Puppet is like the burn version of "Tenpai Dragon." They know the FTK is coming, they try as much as possible to stop it, but it still succeeds! As Quattro would often say... "NOW THAT'S TRUE FANSERVICE!"
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
While Gimmick Puppet is played "pure," it uses a Horus package to support the strategy. Finally, a the staples consist of a Crossout with it's targets to enable the FTK combo to go through as much as possible. 
 
The GIMMICK PUPPET cards constitute the main strategy, forming the majority of the deck. Due to the consistency boosts from the new INFO support, the deck core is relatively small. Rouge Doll, Little Soldiers, Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls and Condolence Puppet are all used at 3 since they are starters. Two each of Terror Baby, Cattle Scream and Argent Chaos Force are used since they are garnets and mostly need to be searched from deck as part of the combo. Terraforming and Set Rotation are both 1 card starters, since they search Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls. Finally, Service Puppet Play is the search target for Fanatix Machinix, enabling the deck to interrupt the opponent if they manage to survive the burn FTK. 
 
A HORUS engine is used to enable rank 8 plays and to give Set Rotation another target to go into. King's Sarcophagus is also a great discard outlet for cards you want to get out of your hand, like if you happen to draw your garnets of Bisque Doll and Terror Baby who have beneficial effects in the GY. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES. Since Gimmick Puppets are very consistent with the new support from INFO, this deck can field quite a few staples. These staples were chosen specifically to enable the FTK to go through as much as possible, so 3 Crossout with it's targeted handtraps with 1 Called By are used. 
 
While this deck needs to be consistent, so it is 40 cards sharp to enable to FTK to go though with as much protection as possible. 
 
For siding in games 2/3 the best cards to take out are x1 Cattle Scream, x1 Argent Chaos Force, x1 Condolence Puppet, x3 Crossout, and any number of match-irrelevant handtraps. In the sidedeck, x1 Shifter and x1 D-Barrier are included as Crossout targets, should you think your opponent side those in vs. you.  
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Gimmick Puppets are infamous for being an extremely effective FTK burn strategy. Gimmick Puppet is almost like the burn version of "Tenpai Dragon." The fieldspell searches a starter, and it renders Gimmick Puppet monsters nigh untouchable as you weave through the combo. 
 
Here are several burn FTK combos for Gimmick Puppet: 
 
Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls = Burn for 9300 + Service Puppet Play (Steal opponent's monsters)
  1. Activate Mansion of the Underworld Dolls. Add from hand Little Soldiers.  
  2. Normal Little Soldier, send to GY Rouge Doll. 
  3. Activate Rouge Doll's GY effect to add it from the GY to hand. 
  4. Activate Rouge Doll's hand effect to summon herself hand, reveal any rank 8 from Extra Deck and summon Cattle Scream from deck. 
  5. XYZ summon Fantasix Makina using Little Soldiers and Cattle Scream. 
  6. Activate Fantasix Makina's effect to detach Cattle Scream and add from deck Rank-Up Magic Argent Chaos Force. 
  7. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  8. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Dark Strings. 
  9. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Cattle Scream and Rouge Doll. 
  10. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  11. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Dark Strings. 
  12. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into another Dark Strings. 
  13. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3300 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY. 
  14. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  15. Activate Mansion's effect to detach 1 material from your Dark Strings on the field to summon the Dark Strings in the GY to your opponent's field. 
  16. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank up into the Chaos version of the card: CXYZ Gimmick Puppet Fanatix Makinix. 
  17. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  18. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Puppet of Strings. 
  19. Link summon Chimera Doll using Fanatix + Dark Strings. 
  20. Activate Chimera Doll's effect to add from deck Terror Baby. 
  21. Normal summon Terror Baby to summon from GY Cattle Scream. 
  22. Banish Little Soldiers from GY targeting Terror Baby to make it a level 8. 
  23. XYZ summon Giant Grinder using Terror Baby + Cattle Scream. 
  24. Detach from Giant Grinder twice targeting both Dark Strings and Puppet of Strings on your opponent's side of the field to burn for 3300 and 3000. You burn your opponent for a grand total of 9300!
Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls = Burn for 8100 + Draw 3 cards + Service Puppet Play (Steal opponent's monsters)
 
  1. Repeat steps 1-6 from the first combo. 
  2. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Fanatix Makinix. 
  3. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  4. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Fanatix Makinix. 
  5. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Rouge Doll and Cattle Scream. 
  6. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  7. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Fanatix Makinix. 
  8. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Cattle Scream. 
  9. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  10. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3100 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY.
  11. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand. 
  12. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Cattle Scream on your opponent's field. 
  13. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings. 
  14. Activate Dark String's trigger effect again to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 2000 (the ATK of the destroyed Cattle Scream).
  15. Activate Mansion's effect to detach 1 material from your Dark Strings on the field to summon the Puppet of Strings in the GY to your opponent's field. 
  16. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Puppet of Strings on your opponent's field. 
  17. Link summon Chimera Doll using Dark Strings + Dark Strings. 
  18. Activate Chimera Doll's effect to add from deck Terror Baby.
  19. Normal summon Terror Baby to summon from GY Dark Strings.
  20. Activate Dark String's trigger effect for the third time to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3000 (the ATK of the destroyed Puppet of Strings). You burn your opponent for a grand total of 8100 AND draw 3 cards in the process!
 
Little Soldiers + Any Level 8 Gimmick Puppet = 
 
  1. Repeat steps 1-6 from the first combo.
  2. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Fanatix Makinix.
  3. Activate Fanatix Makinix's effect to add a Gimmick Puppet trap from your deck (typically Service Puppet Play). If your opponent manages to live to the next turn, you still have an interruption!
  4. Summon Cattle Scream from the GY by detaching a material from Fanatix Makinix.
  5. XYZ summon Puppet of Strings using Rouge Doll and Cattle Scream.
  6. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand.
  7. Activate Puppet of Strings effect to place a String Counter on Fanatix Makinix.
  8. Activate Fanatix's effect detaching 1 card to summon to your opponent's side of the field Cattle Scream.
  9. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Puppet of Strings to rank it up into Dark Strings.
  10. Activate Dark String's trigger effect in CL1 to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw 1 card, and burn your opponent for 3100 (the ATK of the destroyed Dark Strings). In CL2, activate Fantasix Makina's effect to summon itself from the GY.
  11. Activate Argent Chaos Force's trigger effect in the GY to add itself back to hand.
  12. Detach a material from Dark Strings to put a String counter on Cattle Scream on your opponent's field.
  13. Activate Argent Chaos Force targeting Fantasix Makina to rank it up into Dark Strings.
  14. Activate Dark String's trigger effect again to destroy as many monsters with String Counters as possible, draw another 1 card, and burn your opponent for 2000 (the ATK of the destroyed Cattle Scream).
 
You can also more or less replicate either combo without Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls by having Little Soldiers + any level 8 Gimmick Puppet. The only difference is that your Gimmick Puppet Monsters on the field will be affected by your opponent's non-XYZ monster effects, especially handtraps. If you also lack a level 8 body, Horus monsters are excellent extenders. 
 
Unlike other FTK decks, Gimmick Puppets actually do well at breaking boards, especially while Mansion is active. Going second, Gimmick Puppets naturally break boards as they combo through Gigantes Doll, Giant Grinder, Puppet of Strings and Dark Strings. All the while, Mansion of Dreadful Doll renders your monsters nearly invincible vs. your opponent's monster-based interruption (except XYZ monsters like Zeus and TY-Phon). Horus monsters paired with Gold Sarcophagus remove monsters through the battle phase effectively as well. 

 
GENERAL TIPS
  • The Horus monsters are excellent extenders if you lack a level 8 body to XYZ summon with. The Horus cards also excel at removal of hard to out monsters in the Battle Phase. 
  • Despite your Gimmick Puppet monsters not affected on the field while Mansion is active, you're still vulnerable to handtraps like Droll, Shifter, Imperm and Bystials. Remember, this deck has many extenders (Horus, Biqsue Doll, Chimera Doll, Terror Baby) so you can still potentially play through those specific handtraps!
  • For siding in games 2/3 the best cards to take out are x1 Cattle Scream, x1 Argent Chaos Force, x1 Condolence Puppet, x3 Crossout, and any number of match-irrelevant handtraps. In the sidedeck, x1 Shifter and x1 D-Barrier are included as Crossout targets, should you think your opponent side those in vs. you.  
  • If your FTK have been interrupted into a standstill and you lack resources to complete the shift, the trap card Service Puppet Play is your next play. Summon as many XYZ monsters as possible so you can quick effect steal your opponent's monsters. 
  • The FTK combo is very easy to mess up since every move is very exact and calculated. You can get interrupted midway as well, so your opponent can survive the FTK Practice makes perfect!
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Recently, Konami keeps pretty insane field spells for archetypes they want to see meta competitive play. Almost like how Invoked has "Magical Meltdown," the fieldspell renders your archetypal cards unaffected! First Tenpai, then Yubel, and now out of nowhere... Gimmick Puppet?! 
 
Gimmick Puppet certainly has made it's own unique niche as the competitive "burn deck!" Despite how degenerate and un-interactive it is, it's kind of exciting that in a tier 0 format dominated by ridiculously expensive 1-card combo engines that burn FTK can make its mark. 
 
Being a burn FTK is kind of thematically relevant too, since your opponent doesn't get to play - all they do is watch in awe as you control the strings of the horrific puppet show! In the words of Quattro... "NOW THAT'S TRUE FANSERVICE!"
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: My gaia curse of dragon deck

deck_description:
3x Realm of Light with a few extradeck mosnters from other releases. (Used the baseline) blatantly copied the main deck from Casual Duelist from here: 3x Realm of Light Structure Deck Profile July 2024

REALM OF LIGHT

Mission number one is to summon Vice-Madame and keep her on the board at all cost...She is your bread and butter.

(How to summon Vice-Madame your turn one... Blazing Cartesia - Quick Effect, Witchcrafter Confusion Confession from hand or summon Schmietta use her Quick Effect to summon Genni and send Genni to the GY by link summoning her away with Artemis - From there you use Schmietta GY effect to send Confusion Confession from the deck to the GY and use Genni GY effect to copy the effect of Confusion Confession - You can use Artemis plus any witchcrafter monster to summon Vice-Madame - Creation and Reasoning will help you get other witchcrafters to go with Artemis if you don't already have targets in hand or on the board - If you have enough spells in your hands you may also go into Haine - Verre or Aruru using Genni Quick Effect rather then using Artemis to link Genni to the GY - From there you do as listed above with the GY effects to summon Vice-Madame, Branded In High Spirits - As the card says you will use a target in hand and Dusk Dragon - sending them to the GY and deck search Blazing Cartesia - from there you will use Blazing's Quick Effect to Fusion summon Vice-Madame)

Tips : Try and leave Blazing Cartesia on the field if possible as she is your Tuner to go into your Synchro's. You will get the 2ed material often with Vice-Madame's special summon effect for a lower level witchcrafter you will will just summon the level you need to with Cartesia's level 4. If you can wait and use your spell cards after you summon Vice-Madame so you can triger Vice's effects as she will triger off of spell cards you can also use your GY spellcaster effects or just on feild spellcaster effects to do the same thing.

From there you just try and build a board that you think will stop your opponent and what you can't stop keep it from hurting you so in your 2ed turn you can hopefully take the victory with a well time negates, pops and protections.

I'm still vary much still playing with this deck in terms of a few cards and learning new things about the deck. Witchcrafters is not really a super strong deck and even from a casual stand point the core deck feels vary weak in terms of where YuGiOh is today. My goal was make the deck feel a bit stronger and playable on a modest budget. I find the deck to be a vary fun deck to pilot and I encourage anyone thinking of playing or playing Witchcrafters to play around with this deck and make changes as need be. I think this is a great baseline if nothing else to build off of.

Just a Red-Eyes deck.

Dark Dragoon is going to be your boss monster. You can get him into the game by using Red-Eyes Fusion, which this deck has no trouble searching out. You can use Red-Eyes Insight to send a Red-Eyes monster from your Deck to the GY in order to add a Red-Eyes Fusion (or any other Red-Eyes spell/trap) from your Deck to your hand. A great target to send to the GY is Red-Eyes Black Meteor Dragon, as you can banish him from the GY (as long he wasn't sent to the GY the turn you want to use his effect) to get a Red-Eyes Fusion from your Deck or GY. You can also send a Red-Eyes Black Dragon with Insight to Special Summon with Red-Eyes Spirit, Return of the Red-Eyes, or Red-Eyes Black Flare Dragon.

deck_name: Alexis Rhodes Tag Force Deck - Cyber Angel ‚òÖ6
deck_excerpt: The deck of the Cyber Angel herself!
deck_description:
I wanted to make a writeup of this deck on my lunch break. This is one of Alexis' decks from Tag Force 2. This one stuck out to me because it's actually well-built compared to earlier iterations of the strategy - it also makes for better anime duels since it's not a guaranteed blowout. I'll write this out in the same order the cards are listed above so it's easy to follow.

Our first card is Cyber Prima . Prima is a decent beater that can be summoned with one tribute. Its effect allows you to destroy all face up continuous spells on the field. 1x is good because it's situational.

Our next card is 2x Soul of Purity and Light .  This card can be summoned by banishing two light monsters from the graveyard (this deck runs a lot) and gains 300 ATK during your opponents battle phase. A great old school card in my opinion.

Next, we have 2x Harvest Angel of Wisdom . When destroyed by battle, it can grab a counter spell trap from your graveyard. This deck runs 7 of those, so it helps recycle some of the best cards in the deck.

The next three are non-engine so I'll put them all in one section. Sangan helps search, Marshmallon helps stall, and Morphing Jar helps alleviate bricked hands. All three are limited one and good inclusions in the list.

Next, we have our two fusion pieces for Cyber Blader. 2x Etoile Cyber and 2x Blade Skater . Both of these cards are hard bricks by this point, so I'm not even going to say much about them. At the very least, they can't be beat over by an opponents Sangan or a floater (ex. Mother Grizzly) while they are in defense position.

Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands lets you grab a ritual spell or ritual monster from your deck. Pretty self-explanatory. This deck plays 3x.

Senju of the Thousand Hands can grab you a ritual monster from your deck. I think they went too hard with these guys in the deck. There aren't really enough ritual monsters in this deck to justify running 3x, but we'll just have to deal with it. If you're going to change this build, just play 1x.

Next, we have 2x Cyber Angel Dakini . Dakini is one of the shining stars of this deck. Not only can she make your opponent send a monster to the graveyard (non-targeting, non-destruction), but she also deals piercing damage and can recycle ritual monsters/spells from the graveyard.

Cyber Angel Benten is an 1800 ATK beater. If she destroys an enemy in battle, your opponent will be burned for the original DEF of the monster destroyed. Her better effect, however, is letting you grab a light fairy monster from deck if you tribute her for a ritual summon.

The last monster is 1x Cyber Angel Idaten . Idaten is a defensive wall that can recycle a ritual spell from the graveyard or add one from deck to hand. If tributed for a ritual summon, she gives all your ritual monsters +1000 ATK (permanently).

Onto the spells/traps, we first have Machine Angel Ritual . This is a necessary 3x for this deck in order to get our Angels out on the field. Its AMAZING secondary effect protects from battle or card destruction at the cost of banishing it from the graveyard.

Next, we have 2x Polymerization . This is here just for Cyber Blader.

Followed by 2x Reinforcement of the Army  for searching out our fusion pieces.

Next, we have Premature Burial and Swords of Revealing Light . Premature is a self-explanatory great card, and Swords like Marshmallon will help us stall if bricking.

Finally, the traps! Call of the Haunted is another standard 1x for the same reason as Premature Burial.

Miraculous Descent is a great card that can summoned back any fairy type monster you may have banished with Soul of Purity and Light .

And finally, our counter trap lineup! These can all be recycled with Harvest Angel of Wisdom . 2x Divine Wrath helps us negate monster effects. I'll be honest, I wasn't crazy about them including this card in the list. In Tag Force, it's often a dead draw against NPCs.

Next, we have 2x Magic Drain . This is actually a solid card - while inherently a neg 1 it can often force your opponent to go neg 1. Also, if all they have in hand is a Snatch Steal, they have to think VERY carefully about how to respond...

1x Negate Attack is included to help preserve your field or preserve your life points.

Finally, we have 2x Solemn Judgment . Is there anything really to say about this card? It's one of the best cards ever printed. Use it wisely! 2x is a good ratio because often if you open with it, halving your life points when you're at full can be very risky.

And that's it! I hope you had fun reading this, I had fun writing it up.

deck_excerpt: Effectively dead if Beatrice is banned lol
deck_description: Just something I've been messing with for a bit trying to see if I could make Nordics at last somewhat playable, works well enough I think...!!! Pretty simple, for your full combo you just need at least Rite of Aramesir, any of the fiendsmith cards and at least 1 Nordic in hand to start you off(mainly Alviss), if you don't start with this setup, that's your fault and Odin doesn't love you. Chicken game + terraforming are just there as filler since I didn't really know what else to put, feel free to take em out but the extra draw can help if that's anything I guess. The basic play is summoning an adventurer token (do not put the token or anything else that you want to stay on the field in a spot that blocks the Nordic link's arrow, leave that clear for an aesir) and once fateful adventure is set, activate any of the fiendsmith cards you may have and get lurrie, discard him and once summoned just get requiem out, then engraver, equip requiem to engraver and summon necroquip and summon engraver with his own effect from the grave. At any point during this fateful adventure will ask to add or equip dracoback, just add it, it's better if it's in your hand for certain applications, then search for gryphon rider and discard dracoback so you can equip it to the token. XYZ summon Beatrice with Necro and engraver and send the nordic throne spell (I'm not spelling that shit) and search any Nordic monster you want and send the least important card in your hand back to the deck. Ideally you'd want Alviss as one of the 2 Nordics in hand otherwise you'll have to sacrifice a good chunk of your field and hand to summon an aesir. Normal whatever Nordic you have and link it off into Gullveig and banish Alviss, then summon Ivaldi, activate Ivaldi, search for Svalinn then activate Alviss, send any of the Nordic beasts to the gy and summon one of the aesirs into the zone Gullveig points to (mainly Odin, it doesn't matter too much but you should do this or I will turn you into paste). At this point you're locked so just set svalinn and pass your turn if there's nothing else left to do. On your opponent's turn, send the black goat laughs with Beatrice and activate that whenever's convenient if you know what your opponent's playing, gryphon rider is another negate and svalinn will save your ass every turn. That's pretty much it. Very vulnerable to handtraps n going second but if you pray to the aesirs every day then you don't need to worry about that, losing with Nordics is entirely your fault and you should be ashamed for not believing in the Norse gods. Have fun!!

deck_excerpt: It's all fun and games until you lack the LP to operate your deck...
deck_description: Simple enough to operate. Not overpowered by any means but satisfying to play as you gain enormous amounts of Atk in about 2 turns? heh...

Faith_SC 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This core of this deck is composed of the traditional BRANDED, DESPIA and BYSTIAL cards. Due to the current meta, I've also added back the FRIGHTFUR, SUPERPOLY and NADIR SERVANT packages. 
 
The BYSTIAL package is relatively small, since banishing light/dark monsters in the GY isn't very impactful and common in today's fire-dominated metagame. Lubellion is "searchable" from deck since Branded Fusion dumps him to the GY, and Lubellion can summon itself from the GY by tributing the on-field Albion. Lubellion can place from deck Branded Lost as extra protection/search power or Branded Regained for more advantage generation.
 
SUPERPOLY has been re-added back to the vulnerability of most meta decks to the card. For example, Mannadium boards can be broken by making Muddy Mudragon by fusing away Apollousa and Baronne. Fire King boards can be broken by fusing away Amblowhale and another of their fire monsters. 
 
NADIR SERVANT is an excellent and multi-purpose extender to Branded, since it singlehandidly sets up Quem + Albaz on the field and GY. It can also dump a missing combo piece to the GY to fulfill particular goals, like dumping Rindbrumm (so Albaz can be summoned from GY during opponent's turn) or Albion (so it can set a Branded card from deck). Also, if Branded Fusion gets negated, Nadir Servant still sets up a strong gamestate by itself. 
 
FUSION DEPLOYMENT also functions as a toolbox in this deck, since its 2 targets each serve a distinct function. Albaz can breakboards when summoned, and Albaz + Super Poly cracks most boards nowadays. If your opponent happens to field Dragon monsters, Albaz can contact fuse them away. Cartesia enables fusion summoning as a quick effect. Not only does she give access to Granguinol (which is a foolish burial), she can protect your activating monster effects on the field from targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler. 
 
TRIPLE TACTICS THRUST is an incredible card in a Branded deck, since it can indirectly search you any normal spell/trap if your opponent dares to activate a monster effect during your turn, even Branded Fusion! Going first, this card can set Fusion Duplication, which can copy any normal/quick-play fusion spell from the GY from the GY like Branded Fusion and Super Poly! So say you get Ash'd on Branded Fusion, you can activate Triple Tactics Thrust to set Fusion Duplication from deck and full fusion combo during your opponent's  Draw Phase!
 
50 CARDS are utilized in this deck rather than around 40ish since every important piece (esp. Branded Fusion) is highly searchable anyways. 50 cards also reduces the likelihood of drawing garnets and bricks.
 
The SIDEDECK is chock full of potent boardbreakers when you are forced to go second - Shaddoll Fusion (explained below), Cosmic Cyclone (to kill Fire King Island) and Evenly Matched (searchable with Thrust). The cards to sideout in this deck are the Bystial cards when you aren't facing a dedicated light/dark deck, or 1 copy of Mercourier, Cartesia, and Quem. When forced to go second, you can also side out Fusion Duplication and Branded Regained. Different Dimension Ground and Eradicator Epidemic Virus are turn ending going-first targets for Triple Tactics Thrust. Branded Etude is an excellent searchable floodgate that banishes your opponent's material for summons, hardcountering common meta strategies like Fire Kings, Sinful Spoils and Voiceless Voice. 
 
The SHADDOLL package is in the sidedeck specifically to counter Fire King Sinful Spoils (although the . This package is especially potent going second. Shaddoll Fusion will send from deck to GY Naelshaddoll Ariel and Shaddoll Dragon to summon Shaddoll Apkallone. This will simultaneously banish 3 cards from your opponent's GY(Ariel's eff), destroy 1 spell/trap (Dragon's eff), and negate a card on the field (Apkallone's eff). 3 chainblocked interactions with 1 Shaddoll Fusion makes for a potent boardbreaker! 
 
SUPER POLYMERIZATION is extremely effective this format. Boards are easily crackable with Super Poly's non-targeting, non-destroying removal, eviserating decks like Fire Kings, Voiceless Voice and other Branded variants. The Extra Deck has Garura and Mudragon as it's targets. The Extra Deck is tight, but Earth Golem @Ignister can be slotted in to out the usual Fire King board of I:P Masquerena and Amblowhale/Promethean Princess. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
This is my "Gas" Branded is designed to play through your opponent's interruption to create gigantic fusion beatsticks and overwhelm with high ATK and massive resource generation. If given even a second of breathing space, your opponent will find that they are facing down a field full of powerful fusion monsters!
 
Branded Fusion is both a blessing and a curse for this strategy. The whole deck revolves around searching and resolving that card, and if it's negated, your further options are likely limited. Your obvious glaring chokepoint and weakness is Branded Fusion, so it is imperative that you can bait out the Ash Blossom or other forms of interruption before you activate this card. It is advisable to use every other card first like  Branded Opening or Lubellion so that you can bait out your opponent's interruption (but be careful of Droll). Also, from experience playing the deck, I've discovered that people intentionally hold their Ash Blossom saving it for Branded Fusion - so if you don't have the card, you can bluff having it and just do all your searches/summons from deck!
 
End boards are very hand dependant and can vary greatly, but here are the mainline combos:
 
Branded Fusion + Dark Monster + Discard = Mirrorjade (banish), Bystial Lubellion + Branded Continous Spell (resources), Set Branded Card (Branded in Red, Banishment, Retribution, Opening)
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, sending Albaz + Bystial Lubellion from deck.
  2. Fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon by fusing Albaz + Dark Monster with Albion. Ideal dark monsters to banish are Tragedy (search) and Dramaturge (free body on field).
  3. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling back Albaz from banished pile and Lubellion the Searing Dragon on the field.
  4. Summon Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing Albion.
  5. Activate Lubellion's card effect to activate from deck Branded Regained so it can generate resources. Alternatively, you can activate from deck Branded Lost for further searches/fusion protection. In games 2/3, you can place Branded Etude to banish your opponent's summon material. 
  6. End phase - set your Branded card of choice from deck. Ideally, you set Branded in Red so you can fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If you already have Branded in Red, you can set Branded Opening for further searches/protection from destruction. 
Cartesia + Light/Dark monster + Either Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon = Search for any Branded card (Best to use if you're missing a particular Branded card, esp. Branded Fusion!)
  1. Activate Cartesia's effect to fusion summon Granguinol by using Cartesia + Light/Dark monster. If Saronir is in hand, you use Saronir instead.
  2. Granguinol sends to GY from deck Bystial Saronir. (Or Albion the Shrouded Dragon)
  3. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY Branded Retribution. 
  4. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY your Branded spell/trap card of choice. 
  5. Banish Branded Retribution from GY to retrieve from GY your Branded spell/trap of choice.
Nadir Servant = Albaz's "Superpoly" + Mirrorjade's banish 
  1. Activate Nadir Servant sending Titaniklad from Extra deck to GY searching from deck either Quem or Albaz. 
  2. During the End Phase, Titaniklad summons Quem from deck. 
  3. Quem activates her effect on-summon, sending Albaz to the GY. 
  4. During your opponent's turn, Quem summons Albaz from GY so he can fuse your opponent's Extra Deck monster away into Mirrorjade.
 
Going first and uninterrupted, your opponent will likely contend with Mirrorjade's banish and a set Branded spell/trap (likely Branded in Red, Retribution or Banishment). Depending on the hand, your opponent may also be dealing with Mercourier's monster negate, bystial's GY banish, Masquerade's -600 burn, and Granguinol can summon Luluwalilith from the Extra Deck. If you're lucky, you also have a facedown Super Polymerization - a devasting turn ending card if used at the right time. Your hand will likely also be sizeable and ready with follow-up for next turn since Cartesia, Titaniklad and Albion generate resources during Branded's "main phase 3" - the End Phase.
 
Going second, Branded can slog through interruption, pierce through boards and beat down your opponent's monsters with big beatsticks. Branded is naturally equipped with in-engine ways to play going second. Polymerization fusing into Guardian Chimera is a nigh-unstoppable juggernaut since it's effect is often chainblocked with the fusion material used for it's fusion summon and it is untargetable since you used Polymerization. If Branded Opening is in the GY, it also can't be destroyed! Super Polymerization can fuse away many boards in today's meta, especially with Garura, only needing 2 monsters with the same type and attribute. Muddy Mudragon can fuse away your Fire King's opponent's Amblowhale + Fire Monster as well! Alot of interruption these days involve destroying and banishing (For example, Fire King and Labrynth does this alot) - Branded is very comfortable with all those interruptions and it usually shrugs them off. 
 
While being able to play through the "Tier 1 Fire" meta, Branded can also compete easily vs. the "anti-meta" strategies that hardcounter the tier 0 fire decks. The strategies that love to lockout the GY like Kashtira, Exosister and Floowandereeze are all good matchups for Branded. Dimension Shifter, Nibiru and Droll & Lockbird are all high impact handtraps that Albaz and friends can comfortably play through with most hands!
 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Due to the relevance of Droll & Lockbird this format, try to search for Branded Fusion first before anything else. Once they Droll you after you get this crucial playstarter, the lingering search floodgate hardly affects the Branded strategy since everything else summons or sets directly from the maindeck.
  • Try to bait out Ash Blossom by your many searches/summons from deck before you use Branded Fusion. If you don't have Branded Fusion, your opponent will likely hold Ash Blossom in their hand waiting for it, so you can bluff having the card to search/summon all you want!
  • Branded lacks in-engine ways to remove backrow, except with Guardian Chimera. Be sure to side in the ample amounts of backrow hate in these match-ups! 
  • Try to have Cartesia on board before you summon monsters on the field with important effects. Cartesia's quick effect fusion summon allows you to dodge common targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler.
  • The best cards to side out is the Bystial and Edge Imp package, especially when the match-ups doesn't call for them. Super Polymerization can also be sided out in certain matchups where your Super Poly targets don't work out.
  • If Branded Lost is active, Fusion effect's activation cannot be negated. Cards that negate the activation like Baronne De Fleur, Borreload Savage Dragon and even Solemn Judgment cannot negate your Branded Fusion! Branded Lost is a perfect way to bait a negate or to guarantee your Fusion effect when you're against these threats.
  • If you feel like it's a good meta call, play Dragoon in Branded! Include Dark Magician/The Light-Hex Sealed Fusion and Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon in your deck for an indestructible and untargetable powerhouse!
  • Some decks immediately die to Branded Etude since it's a "macro-cosmos" for Extra Deck summons. In particular, Fire King/Diabellestarr variants flop to this searchable floodgate. Many rogue decks also are crippled by Etude like Voiceless Voice, Chimera and Spright. 
  • Instant Fusion can summon either Millenium-Eyes Restrict (self-explanatory) or Mudragon of the Swamp. Mudragon of the Swamp lowkey hardcounters Fire Kings strategies, since calling "fire" with Mudragon makes it impossible for your opponent's monsters to target themselves - rendering the deck nigh unplayable! For example, Kirin and Promethean Princess wouldn't be able to activate!
